00:03:23.060 --> 00:03:24.729
to get a nice
perfectly poached eggs.

00:03:24.729 --> 00:03:26.770
And you'll find that
there's people that tell you

00:03:26.770 --> 00:03:28.870
many different ways to do it.

00:03:28.870 --> 00:03:33.520
What I was taught was that you
take the pot, you have water,

00:03:33.520 --> 00:03:34.770
you salt the water.

00:03:34.770 --> 00:03:37.930
Actually I am going to salt
the water for a little bit.

00:03:37.930 --> 00:03:39.610
You salt the water.

00:03:39.610 --> 00:03:42.390
And then I was told to
put vinegar in the water,

00:03:42.390 --> 00:03:45.090
because it helps the egg white
settle a little bit faster.

00:03:45.090 --> 00:03:49.280
And then I was taught to stir
a vortex into it like this,

00:03:49.280 --> 00:03:51.500
break my eggs into a
separate little container,

00:03:51.500 --> 00:03:53.820
and then pour it gently into
the middle of that vortex.

00:03:53.820 --> 00:03:56.090
And supposedly the
vortex is supposed

00:03:56.090 --> 00:04:00.220
to help you maintain like a
nice sort of for torpedo shape.

00:04:00.220 --> 00:04:02.360
The idea is that as it
falls into that vortex,

00:04:02.360 --> 00:04:03.521
it swirls around like this.

00:04:03.521 --> 00:04:05.270
And because the egg
white and the egg yolk

00:04:05.270 --> 00:04:07.604
have a different density it
kind of leaves like a trail,

00:04:07.604 --> 00:04:09.020
kind of like a
comet going around.

00:04:09.020 --> 00:04:10.490
So the yolk will
go in the front,

00:04:10.490 --> 00:04:11.850
the white will trail behind it.

00:04:11.850 --> 00:04:13.460
And that's supposed to give
it a really nice shape.

00:04:13.460 --> 00:04:15.589
But in reality, what
happens is you end up

00:04:15.589 --> 00:04:16.589
breaking half your eggs.

00:04:16.589 --> 00:04:18.047
They swirl around
in there and then

00:04:18.047 --> 00:04:21.262
you end up with egg drop soup
and you have to start over.

00:04:21.262 --> 00:04:21.970
And it's not fun.

00:04:21.970 --> 00:04:22.800
It's not fun.

00:04:22.800 --> 00:04:25.020
Any line cookers who had
to poach a lot of eggs

00:04:25.020 --> 00:04:26.320
can tell you it's not easy.

00:04:26.320 --> 00:04:29.720
So what we're actually
going to do instead

00:04:29.720 --> 00:04:32.340
is we're going to take our eggs.

00:04:32.340 --> 00:04:33.047
These are eggs.

00:04:33.047 --> 00:04:34.422
I already showed
you eggs before,

00:04:34.422 --> 00:04:36.515
didn't I. Now the one
thing you want to do,

00:04:36.515 --> 00:04:37.890
you want to make
sure when you're

00:04:37.890 --> 00:04:40.780
poaching eggs is that your
eggs are really, really fresh.

00:04:40.780 --> 00:04:43.887
You want them to be like
within a couple weeks of having

00:04:43.887 --> 00:04:44.970
coming out of the chicken.

00:04:44.970 --> 00:04:47.504
If you can get them like the
day of, that's even better.

00:04:47.504 --> 00:04:49.420
But what happens is--
let me break open an egg

00:04:49.420 --> 00:04:50.586
and show you something here.

00:04:54.580 --> 00:05:02.040
So when you break open an
egg, immediately what you see

00:05:02.040 --> 00:05:03.090
is obviously two things.

00:05:03.090 --> 00:05:05.000
There is the white and the yolk.

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:07.730
But actually there are really
three phases in an egg.

00:05:07.730 --> 00:05:10.270
So there is the yolk, which
is inside its own little sack,

00:05:10.270 --> 00:05:11.072
its own membrane.

00:05:11.072 --> 00:05:13.280
There's the white, which is
also in its own membrane.

00:05:13.280 --> 00:05:16.610
But then there's also
all this loose white,

00:05:16.610 --> 00:05:18.470
which is not within
that same little sack

00:05:18.470 --> 00:05:21.010
as the main part of the white.

00:05:21.010 --> 00:05:24.030
And that excess loose
weight, that's the problem.

00:05:24.030 --> 00:05:27.162
That's what makes your
eggs fall apart in there.

00:05:27.162 --> 00:05:29.620
JENNA TAYLOR: That's what gets
all wispy and flying around.

00:05:29.620 --> 00:05:30.030
J. KENJI LOPEZ-ALT: Exactly.

00:05:30.030 --> 00:05:31.154
That's what gets all wispy.

00:05:31.154 --> 00:05:34.690
And the thing is the
older your egg is,

00:05:34.690 --> 00:05:37.292
the weaker the membranes
in there are going to be.

00:05:37.292 --> 00:05:38.750
So the higher the
chance it's going

00:05:38.750 --> 00:05:40.350
to be that you're going to
break your eggs when it falls

00:05:40.350 --> 00:05:42.808
into the water or that there's
going to be too much of that

00:05:42.808 --> 00:05:43.500
lose white.

00:05:43.500 --> 00:05:45.070
So what you really
want to do when

00:05:45.070 --> 00:05:47.270
you're going to poach eggs is
find the freshest eggs you can.

00:05:47.270 --> 00:05:49.570
There's a couple ways you
can tell how fresh an egg is.

00:05:49.570 --> 00:05:51.540
The first one is
just look at the box,

00:05:51.540 --> 00:05:53.550
because they all
have a sell by date.

00:05:53.550 --> 00:05:57.480
The sell by date by law has
to be within 30 days at a time

00:05:57.480 --> 00:05:59.980
that the egg was
packed into the carton.

00:05:59.980 --> 00:06:02.030
But it can be anywhere
within that 30 day range.

00:06:02.030 --> 00:06:03.650
So the real number
you're looking for

00:06:03.650 --> 00:06:05.400
is what's called the
Julian date and it'll

00:06:05.400 --> 00:06:08.790
be a three digit number on the
carton right next to the sell

00:06:08.790 --> 00:06:09.290
by date.

00:06:09.290 --> 00:06:11.310
And that three digit
number is the day

00:06:11.310 --> 00:06:13.660
that the eggs were packed on.

00:06:13.660 --> 00:06:15.990
It goes one to 365, obviously.

00:06:15.990 --> 00:06:18.980
And as I just
found out, when you

00:06:18.980 --> 00:06:21.534
search for what is the
252nd day of the year,

00:06:21.534 --> 00:06:23.450
Google doesn't immediately
give you an answer.

00:06:23.450 --> 00:06:25.034
You have to go to a chart.

00:06:25.034 --> 00:06:26.450
So maybe somebody
can get on that.

00:06:26.450 --> 00:06:29.170
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:29.170 --> 00:06:30.890
If you really have
no idea, another way

00:06:30.890 --> 00:06:37.710
you can tell your eggs is
by you get a cup of water

00:06:37.710 --> 00:06:41.720
and-- I don't know how many of
you've really closely looked

00:06:41.720 --> 00:06:43.330
at a hard boiled egg.

00:06:43.330 --> 00:06:47.755
I'm sure most of you here
have eaten a hard boiled egg.

00:06:47.755 --> 00:06:49.880
When you peel a hard boiled
egg along this fat end,

00:06:49.880 --> 00:06:51.379
you sometimes see
this little divot,

00:06:51.379 --> 00:06:52.990
this little bubble in there.

00:06:52.990 --> 00:06:54.531
And that bubble is
in there naturally

00:06:54.531 --> 00:06:56.390
and it always
forms on this side.

00:06:56.390 --> 00:06:59.210
As the egg gets
older and older--

00:06:59.210 --> 00:07:03.490
the shell is slightly porous so
it will actually lose moisture

00:07:03.490 --> 00:07:06.860
and particularly in the
US, because eggs in the US

00:07:06.860 --> 00:07:09.530
are washed before packing.

00:07:09.530 --> 00:07:11.220
So when it comes
out of the chicken,

00:07:11.220 --> 00:07:13.690
there's this kind of
natural waxy cuticle on it

00:07:13.690 --> 00:07:15.730
that is also a weather barrier.

00:07:15.730 --> 00:07:17.590
So European eggs--
you might notice

00:07:17.590 --> 00:07:20.000
if you go to Europe, eggs are
stored at room temperature,

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:21.810
whereas in the US they're
stored in the fridge.

00:07:21.810 --> 00:07:23.470
And the reason for that
is because in Europe they

00:07:23.470 --> 00:07:25.720
don't wash the eggs after
they come out of the chicken

00:07:25.720 --> 00:07:27.170
so that waxy cuticle is intact.

00:07:27.170 --> 00:07:29.780
So it actually helps protect
the egg from losing moisture.

00:07:29.780 --> 00:07:33.060
It also helps protect it
from bacterial infection

00:07:33.060 --> 00:07:33.907
from the outside.

00:07:33.907 --> 00:07:35.240
In the US, they wash them first.

00:07:35.240 --> 00:07:37.031
So they start out
cleaner, but they're also

00:07:37.031 --> 00:07:38.425
more vulnerable to other things.

00:07:38.425 --> 00:07:40.550
But anyhow, what happens
is the moisture comes out.

00:07:40.550 --> 00:07:42.675
And as the moisture comes
out, that bubble in there

00:07:42.675 --> 00:07:43.700
gets bigger and bigger.

00:07:43.700 --> 00:07:45.690
So a very, very
fresh egg-- and we're

00:07:45.690 --> 00:07:48.350
going to see how
fresh this one is.

00:07:48.350 --> 00:07:49.020
So there you go.

00:07:49.020 --> 00:07:52.960
A very, very fresh egg will
lay on its side like that.

00:07:52.960 --> 00:07:55.100
As the egg gets older
and older, you're

00:07:55.100 --> 00:07:57.397
going to see that it's
going to start floating.

00:07:57.397 --> 00:07:59.730
Well, initially it'll start
standing up with its fat end

00:07:59.730 --> 00:08:01.390
up.

00:08:01.390 --> 00:08:03.350
And eventually if it
gets really, really old

00:08:03.350 --> 00:08:04.300
it's going to actually float.

00:08:04.300 --> 00:08:05.758
And at that point,
you don't really

00:08:05.758 --> 00:08:10.055
want to do anything other
than throw it at people.

00:08:10.055 --> 00:08:11.680
So these are fresh
eggs, which is good.

00:08:15.240 --> 00:08:17.800
But as I pointed out,
even with a very fresh egg

00:08:17.800 --> 00:08:20.190
there's still a good amount
of that really liquidy white

00:08:20.190 --> 00:08:21.160
and that's your enemy.

00:08:21.160 --> 00:08:25.620
So the secret to getting rid of
that is you just use a strainer

00:08:25.620 --> 00:08:30.260
and you just pour your
egg right in there

00:08:30.260 --> 00:08:33.320
and you can see all the
liquid white drips off.

00:08:33.320 --> 00:08:34.820
And that's all stuff
that would have

00:08:34.820 --> 00:08:37.857
gone into your pot of water
and clotted it up and made

00:08:37.857 --> 00:08:38.940
those little wispy things.

00:08:38.940 --> 00:08:44.049
And once you have your basically
clean, tight white and tight

00:08:44.049 --> 00:08:47.360
yolk in there, you
can very gently

00:08:47.360 --> 00:08:54.310
lower it into the water like
this and just kind roll it out.

00:08:54.310 --> 00:08:56.575
And is there a way for
people to see in there?

00:08:56.575 --> 00:08:58.950
I don't know if there's a way
for people to see in there.

00:08:58.950 --> 00:08:59.825
But it looks awesome.

00:08:59.825 --> 00:09:02.950
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:03.710 --> 00:09:06.614
And then once it's in there you
give it a couple little stirs.

00:09:06.614 --> 00:09:08.030
One thing you don't
want to happen

00:09:08.030 --> 00:09:11.540
is for that egg to
stick on the bottom,

00:09:11.540 --> 00:09:14.604
because even though
you're in a pot of water

00:09:14.604 --> 00:09:16.020
the metal on the
bottom of the pot

00:09:16.020 --> 00:09:17.820
is going to conduct
heat into the egg

00:09:17.820 --> 00:09:20.780
obviously faster
than the water is.

00:09:20.780 --> 00:09:23.460
So you want to make sure
this is moving a little bit.

00:09:23.460 --> 00:09:26.890
And this is just going to take
about maybe 30, 45 seconds

00:09:26.890 --> 00:09:28.360
to a minute.

00:09:28.360 --> 00:09:30.090
And once you have
an egg in there

00:09:30.090 --> 00:09:31.520
you can do any number of them.

00:09:31.520 --> 00:09:33.680
It gets pretty easy once
you get going at this.

00:09:39.280 --> 00:09:44.141
Egg whites come out
and egg goes in.

00:09:50.880 --> 00:09:54.170
And I think that first one is
nearly done already, actually.

00:09:54.170 --> 00:09:58.510
So I'm just going to
grab a slotted spoon here

00:09:58.510 --> 00:09:59.380
and fish it out.

00:10:06.790 --> 00:10:07.530
And there.

00:10:07.530 --> 00:10:10.800
So you can see it's like
a perfectly tight white.

00:10:10.800 --> 00:10:14.230
There's nothing-- no like
wispy bits coming out.

00:10:14.230 --> 00:10:16.690
This is a picture
perfect poached egg,

00:10:16.690 --> 00:10:18.760
that's what you're looking for.

00:10:18.760 --> 00:10:20.140
