00:39:02.810 --> 00:39:04.960
JENNA TAYLOR: How do you
design experiments varying

00:39:04.960 --> 00:39:06.794
ingredients?

00:39:06.794 --> 00:39:08.740
J. KENJI LOPEZ-ALT:
Well, it's a lot

00:39:08.740 --> 00:39:11.160
like any kind of experiment.

00:39:11.160 --> 00:39:14.300
So the way you design an
experiment a lot of it

00:39:14.300 --> 00:39:17.050
comes down to sort of intuition
and experience in the field.

00:39:17.050 --> 00:39:19.331
So I have a good idea of
what is likely to work.

00:39:19.331 --> 00:39:21.830
And I think that's the case in
any sort of scientific field,

00:39:21.830 --> 00:39:23.480
the difference between
a good scientist

00:39:23.480 --> 00:39:25.229
and a bad scientist
it comes down to a lot

00:39:25.229 --> 00:39:27.120
to intuition and sort
of general background

00:39:27.120 --> 00:39:29.550
knowledge of the field.

00:39:29.550 --> 00:39:32.550
So yeah, a lot of what I decide
to test comes down to that.

00:39:32.550 --> 00:39:36.600
And then when I'm doing
the actual experiments

00:39:36.600 --> 00:39:39.080
it really is fifth
grade science stuff.

00:39:39.080 --> 00:39:41.439
Isolate the variable,
have a control,

00:39:41.439 --> 00:39:43.480
make sure you eliminate
bias as much as possible.

00:39:47.396 --> 00:39:49.520
I do different types of
recipes and different types

00:39:49.520 --> 00:39:50.160
of experiments.

00:39:50.160 --> 00:39:56.040
So for ones where you can very
easily empirically measure

00:39:56.040 --> 00:39:59.900
things like how well does
mustard emulsify versus an egg

00:39:59.900 --> 00:40:00.430
yolk?

00:40:00.430 --> 00:40:02.846
That one's pretty easy to do,
because it doesn't come down

00:40:02.846 --> 00:40:03.990
to subjective taste.

00:40:03.990 --> 00:40:07.320
A lot of experiments do end up
coming down to subjective case

00:40:07.320 --> 00:40:11.394
and so for those often
it's just my own palate.

00:40:11.394 --> 00:40:13.560
And I think that's one of
the differences between me

00:40:13.560 --> 00:40:15.460
and my former employer
at Cooks Illustrated.

00:40:15.460 --> 00:40:18.480
What we did there was we would
have big panels of people

00:40:18.480 --> 00:40:21.750
tasting-- this one has a half
a teaspoon of lemon juice,

00:40:21.750 --> 00:40:24.540
that one has a teaspoon of lemon
juice, which one do you prefer?

00:40:24.540 --> 00:40:26.670
And so there you end
up with a recipe that

00:40:26.670 --> 00:40:29.560
sort of pleases a lot
of people, but I also

00:40:29.560 --> 00:40:31.700
think lacks personality.

00:40:31.700 --> 00:40:34.740
So what I do is I do the
one that pleases me most

00:40:34.740 --> 00:40:37.460
and explain to you
why it pleases me.

00:40:37.460 --> 00:40:39.907
But if you like less
lemon juice in you thing--

00:40:39.907 --> 00:40:41.490
the idea is that I'm
trying to arm you

00:40:41.490 --> 00:40:43.234
with enough sort
of basic cooking

00:40:43.234 --> 00:40:44.650
technique and
scientific knowledge

00:40:44.650 --> 00:40:47.160
to be able to modify
the ingredient,

00:40:47.160 --> 00:40:48.850
modify the recipe
to your own taste

00:40:48.850 --> 00:40:51.220
and still be sure that
it's going to work.

00:40:51.220 --> 00:40:52.540
JENNA TAYLOR: Excellent.

