do you feel about adding vinegar

00:43:54.650 --> 00:43:55.960
to your poaching
liquid for eggs?

00:43:55.960 --> 00:43:57.380
JENNA TAYLOR: Vinegar
to the poaching liquid?

00:43:57.380 --> 00:43:58.620
How do you feel about it?

00:43:58.620 --> 00:44:01.120
J. KENJI LOPEZ-ALT: So adding
vinegar to the poaching liquid

00:44:01.120 --> 00:44:03.660
the idea there is that
the acidic water is

00:44:03.660 --> 00:44:08.274
going to help the egg white
to set a little bit faster.

00:44:08.274 --> 00:44:10.690
If I was going to poach eggs
using the traditional method,

00:44:10.690 --> 00:44:12.550
I would add vinegar
to the water,

00:44:12.550 --> 00:44:15.720
because you run such a big risk
of the egg white spreading out

00:44:15.720 --> 00:44:16.250
too fast.

00:44:16.250 --> 00:44:18.300
And it does help the egg
whites set a little bit faster.

00:44:18.300 --> 00:44:20.240
But I also find that it
makes like a very sort

00:44:20.240 --> 00:44:23.000
of thin kind of
almost chalky texture

00:44:23.000 --> 00:44:25.090
along the exterior of the egg.

00:44:25.090 --> 00:44:28.244
So using this method you don't
need to worry about the whites.

00:44:28.244 --> 00:44:30.410
So I don't add vinegar,
because I prefer the texture

00:44:30.410 --> 00:44:31.577
without the vinegar.

