00:47:28.202 --> 00:47:30.410
J. KENJI LOPEZ-ALT: Well,
it's actually almost custom

00:47:30.410 --> 00:47:32.610
made for backpacking.

00:47:32.610 --> 00:47:36.120
So in the recipe
the only element

00:47:36.120 --> 00:47:39.700
that I think you have
to leave out is the egg.

00:47:39.700 --> 00:47:43.576
But it has a variety
of emulsifiers in there

00:47:43.576 --> 00:47:44.950
that help that
sauce stay creamy.

00:47:44.950 --> 00:47:46.533
So there's condensed
milk, which comes

00:47:46.533 --> 00:47:48.450
in a can; perfect
for backpacking.

00:47:48.450 --> 00:47:50.200
There's cornstarch.

00:47:50.200 --> 00:47:54.220
And then there's a small amount
of American cheese, which

00:47:54.220 --> 00:47:56.790
contains sodium
citrate, chemical

00:47:56.790 --> 00:48:00.140
salts that help cheeses
melt and stay emulsified.

00:48:00.140 --> 00:48:02.950
And then a large amount
of cheddar cheese.

00:48:02.950 --> 00:48:06.740
So cheeses are good
for backpacking.

00:48:06.740 --> 00:48:09.280
Everything except for the
egg, and then the pasta's dry.

00:48:09.280 --> 00:48:12.030
So and then it all
cooks in one pot.

00:48:12.030 --> 00:48:14.240
You cook the pasta,
you drain it,

00:48:14.240 --> 00:48:16.860
then you throw everything
else in there, and that's it.

00:48:16.860 --> 00:48:19.700
It's pretty easy for
backpacking, actually.

