00:50:43.114 --> 00:50:45.280
JENNA TAYLOR: How are home
cooks wasting their time?

00:50:45.280 --> 00:50:47.202
They can be doing
something more efficient?

00:50:47.202 --> 00:50:49.410
J. KENJI LOPEZ-ALT: I think
mostly it just comes down

00:50:49.410 --> 00:50:51.740
to kitchen organization.

00:50:51.740 --> 00:50:53.470
Particularly, I think,
people waste a lot

00:50:53.470 --> 00:50:57.450
of time becoming cluttered.

00:50:57.450 --> 00:50:59.200
A lot of people will
cook and they'll just

00:50:59.200 --> 00:51:01.570
throw their dirty things as
soon as they're done with them

00:51:01.570 --> 00:51:02.360
they'll leave them
on a cutting board.

00:51:02.360 --> 00:51:04.320
And then you have a
nice big cutting board

00:51:04.320 --> 00:51:07.180
and then you end up with
chopped herbs over here,

00:51:07.180 --> 00:51:08.970
and I have a chopped
onion over here,

00:51:08.970 --> 00:51:10.320
and some pepper skins over here.

00:51:10.320 --> 00:51:11.610
And then you're trying
to work in like a space

00:51:11.610 --> 00:51:13.340
this big and that's
not efficient.

00:51:13.340 --> 00:51:15.697
So I think the number
one way to make yourself

00:51:15.697 --> 00:51:18.030
more efficient in the kitchen
is really clean as you go,

00:51:18.030 --> 00:51:23.550
stay organized, and also think
of yourself as a production

00:51:23.550 --> 00:51:24.051
line.

00:51:24.051 --> 00:51:25.966
Maybe it's not fun way
to think about cooking,

00:51:25.966 --> 00:51:27.880
but I think it makes
it more fun in the end.

00:51:27.880 --> 00:51:31.620
So if you're chopping up five
pounds of onions for an onion

00:51:31.620 --> 00:51:34.474
soup, rather than working
one onion at a time

00:51:34.474 --> 00:51:37.140
and getting it all chopped, I'll
do actually one step at a time.

00:51:37.140 --> 00:51:40.111
So I'll take every onion
and I'll cut off the ends

00:51:40.111 --> 00:51:42.360
and then I'll take every
onion and split them in half.

00:51:42.360 --> 00:51:43.530
Then I'll take every
onion and peel them.

00:51:43.530 --> 00:51:46.070
And that's way you have
less extraneous movements,

00:51:46.070 --> 00:51:49.800
less cleaning up, and it's
much more organized and faster.

00:51:49.800 --> 00:51:51.970
JENNA TAYLOR: How do you
feel about egg politics?

00:51:51.970 --> 00:51:52.550
Cage-free.

00:51:52.550 --> 00:51:53.050
Organic.

00:51:53.050 --> 00:51:53.430
J. KENJI LOPEZ-ALT:
So all right, there's

00:51:53.430 --> 00:51:55.360
two sides to that question.

00:51:55.360 --> 00:51:58.470
There's a flavor side and then
there's the politics side.

00:51:58.470 --> 00:52:00.200
As far as the politics
side go, I think,

00:52:00.200 --> 00:52:03.411
you buy it from best chickens,
the most nicely treated

00:52:03.411 --> 00:52:03.910
chickens.

00:52:03.910 --> 00:52:07.180
I mean, the commercial egg
industry and the dairy industry

00:52:07.180 --> 00:52:09.720
are two of the worst industries
in the world; way, way,

00:52:09.720 --> 00:52:12.970
worse than the meat industries.

00:52:12.970 --> 00:52:17.030
Battery chicken hens are treated
really, really, really poorly.

00:52:17.030 --> 00:52:19.450
So I would recommend
buying cage-free

00:52:19.450 --> 00:52:21.490
if you have a local
farmer even better.

00:52:21.490 --> 00:52:23.800
I would definitely do that
for political reasons.

00:52:23.800 --> 00:52:27.265
As far as flavor reasons
go, a lot of people

00:52:27.265 --> 00:52:28.640
say they can taste
the difference

00:52:28.640 --> 00:52:31.510
between a cage-free egg or a
commercial egg or something

00:52:31.510 --> 00:52:33.284
from their neighbor's yard.

00:52:33.284 --> 00:52:34.950
Every test I've ever
seen and everything

00:52:34.950 --> 00:52:37.280
I've ever done side
by side blind taste

00:52:37.280 --> 00:52:38.820
test you can't tell
the difference.

00:52:38.820 --> 00:52:40.470
They cook the same way.

00:52:40.470 --> 00:52:43.680
They'll have differences
in appearance.

00:52:43.680 --> 00:52:47.740
And this is a test I've done
with large crowds before.

00:52:47.740 --> 00:52:51.530
You can show people two
pictures exactly same egg,

00:52:51.530 --> 00:52:55.194
just photoshop the egg in one of
them a little bit more orange.

00:52:55.194 --> 00:52:57.110
The orange egg is going
to be more appetizing.

00:52:57.110 --> 00:52:59.590
And similarly, if
you're making scramble--

00:52:59.590 --> 00:53:01.280
this is another
brunch tip-- if you

00:53:01.280 --> 00:53:03.720
want your friends to have the
best tasting scrambled eggs

00:53:03.720 --> 00:53:05.390
they've ever had
in their life, just

00:53:05.390 --> 00:53:07.340
add a few drops of orange
food coloring to the eggs

00:53:07.340 --> 00:53:08.550
while you're scrambling them.

00:53:08.550 --> 00:53:10.050
And they'll be like,
oh my god these

00:53:10.050 --> 00:53:12.635
are-- tell them you got them
from your neighbor-- they'll

00:53:12.635 --> 00:53:15.070
be like, oh my god these are
the most flavorful eggs ever.

00:53:15.070 --> 00:53:17.360
And really it's all
just psychosomatic.

00:53:17.360 --> 00:53:19.910
But at the same time, it really
does taste better to them.

00:53:19.910 --> 00:53:21.390
So I think that's a good thing.

00:53:21.390 --> 00:53:26.474
So if can buy better eggs and
knowing the fact that those

00:53:26.474 --> 00:53:28.640
eggs are came from happier
chickens and they're more

00:53:28.640 --> 00:53:30.405
orange, if that actually really
makes it taste better to you

00:53:30.405 --> 00:53:32.720
then it's like, then who cares
if in a blind taste test they

00:53:32.720 --> 00:53:33.010
don't.

00:53:33.010 --> 00:53:33.640
Right?

00:53:33.640 --> 00:53:34.530
That's not what's
important, what's

00:53:34.530 --> 00:53:36.863
important is what's in your
mouth, what's in your brain,

00:53:36.863 --> 00:53:39.300
not what a blind
taste test shows you.

00:53:39.300 --> 00:53:42.740
JENNA TAYLOR: Does
size matter of eggs?

00:53:42.740 --> 00:53:44.360
Only for eggs, clearly.

00:53:44.360 --> 00:53:47.390
J. KENJI LOPEZ-ALT: Yeah, well,
certainly in a baking recipe

00:53:47.390 --> 00:53:50.390
it matters, because yeah
if you use different size

00:53:50.390 --> 00:53:53.260
eggs it's going to throw off
the ratio of baking recipes.

00:53:53.260 --> 00:53:54.220
MALE SPEAKER 2:
What's the right size?

00:53:54.220 --> 00:53:56.280
J. KENJI LOPEZ-ALT: Most recipes
are written for large eggs.

00:53:56.280 --> 00:53:58.240
I like to sometimes
get like jumbo eggs

00:53:58.240 --> 00:54:00.406
if I'm going to poach them
or fry them, because it's

00:54:00.406 --> 00:54:02.240
nice to have a nice big yolk.

00:54:02.240 --> 00:54:04.850
My mom used to go
to a store that

00:54:04.850 --> 00:54:07.053
would sell the double
yolked eggs for fried eggs

00:54:07.053 --> 00:54:08.760
and she really liked those.

00:54:08.760 --> 00:54:10.970
But in general, no.

00:54:10.970 --> 00:54:15.200
As far as flavor and basic
chemical profile goes,

00:54:15.200 --> 00:54:17.070
it doesn't really matter.

00:54:17.070 --> 00:54:19.430
JENNA TAYLOR: The hardest
thing about writing a recipe.

00:54:19.430 --> 00:54:21.820
J. KENJI LOPEZ
ALT: Foolproofing.

00:54:21.820 --> 00:54:24.220
Yeah, it's trying to
figure out everything

00:54:24.220 --> 00:54:28.390
that an end user might do wrong
and guarding against that.

00:54:28.390 --> 00:54:31.660
So when you look at
recipes in this book

00:54:31.660 --> 00:54:35.590
or on Serious Eats or
any place where's there's

00:54:35.590 --> 00:54:38.680
really well written,
well tested recipes,

00:54:38.680 --> 00:54:42.285
you'll find that-- I
always try and offer

00:54:42.285 --> 00:54:44.660
like several different queues
for when something is done.

00:54:44.660 --> 00:54:46.243
So I start with a
visual cues, so I'll

00:54:46.243 --> 00:54:49.140
say cook it until the onions
are translucent and then

00:54:49.140 --> 00:54:52.490
after that I also offer
like a basic timing cue.

00:54:52.490 --> 00:54:54.680
So a poorly written
recipe would be,

00:54:54.680 --> 00:54:58.090
cooked the onions for five
minutes over medium heat.

00:54:58.090 --> 00:55:00.610
And that's poorly written,
because a you don't

00:55:00.610 --> 00:55:04.572
know how much power-- this
one was cooking at 1,000,

00:55:04.572 --> 00:55:05.780
I don't know what that means.

00:55:05.780 --> 00:55:06.320
Is that medium?

00:55:06.320 --> 00:55:06.703
Is that medium?

00:55:06.703 --> 00:55:07.470
I don't know.

00:55:07.470 --> 00:55:10.280
And most people at
home, their gas ranges

00:55:10.280 --> 00:55:13.840
vary so much, so you don't
know what medium heat means.

00:55:13.840 --> 00:55:15.724
Secondly, you don't
know what kind of pan

00:55:15.724 --> 00:55:16.640
they're going to have.

00:55:16.640 --> 00:55:18.050
Are they going to
have an aluminum pan?

00:55:18.050 --> 00:55:19.510
Are they going to have a
really thin nonstick pan?

00:55:19.510 --> 00:55:20.690
Are they going to have
a stainless steel pan?

00:55:20.690 --> 00:55:22.050
So you can specify
all those things,

00:55:22.050 --> 00:55:24.300
but even within the range
of like stainless steel pans

00:55:24.300 --> 00:55:26.550
there's a broad range.

00:55:26.550 --> 00:55:29.390
So it's always much better
to give a visual cue

00:55:29.390 --> 00:55:31.530
and say like, cook the
onions while you're stirring

00:55:31.530 --> 00:55:32.613
until they're translucent.

00:55:32.613 --> 00:55:34.635
This will take about
three to five minutes,

00:55:34.635 --> 00:55:35.760
maybe, something like that.

